<TITLE> Banks, miners lift European shares in early trade </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 FRANKFURT, Feb 12 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - European shares got off to a firm start on Tuesday, lifted by gains in banks and oils, with merger talk helping miners. By 0817 GMT, the pan-European FTSEurofirst 300 index was up 0.9 percent at 1,302.45 points, after the index fell almost 1 percent on Monday. Banking stocks gained after Credit Suisse said it reduced total write-downs from the subprime crisis in dramatic contrast to rising charges by rivals, and raked in billions of new investments from wealthy clients. Its stock rose 0.2 percent. Heavyweight oil shares BP, Shell and Total rose by around 1.2 percent as oil stayed above $93 a barrel. Mining shares gained after the Financial Times reported that Xstrata had rejected a cash-and-shares takeover approach from Brazil's Vale pitched at just under 40 pounds a share, or 39 billion pounds ($76.1 billion). Xstrata shares fell 0.4 percent but rivals Anglo American and BHP Billiton gained more than 2 percent. Elsewhere, Sanofi-Aventis gained 1.9 percent after the French pharmaceuticals group announced a 6.2-percent rise in fourth quarter adjusted net profit and a big rise in its 2007 divide
